explanation:
For a correct MISRA C (string handling) analysis we must examine any code that OS_lseek can call (directly or indirectly) because misuse of <string.h> functions could occur there. The required symbols and why:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee that guards/validates the file descriptor. Must inspect its implementation for any string.h usage (e.g., copying/compares of names).

- OS_GenericSeek_Impl: Direct callee that performs the actual seek behavior; it and its callees may use string operations (buffers, path/name handling) so must be analyzed.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Direct callee invoked on the success path; its implementation may call code that uses string.h functions.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Listed as a callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById. Transaction/init helpers often manipulate names/strings; include to inspect for string.h usage.

- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Converts object IDs to indexes; implementation may validate or operate on name strings or buffers—include to verify no out-of-bounds string ops.

- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Token conversion routine reachable from ObjectIdGetById; include because it may touch token contents or object names using string functions.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Cleanup routine reachable from ObjectIdGetById; include in case it manipulates strings during cancellation.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Callee of OS_GenericSeek_Impl; include since it may access token contents or perform string-like operations.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Callee of OS_ObjectIdRelease; include for the same reason as other transaction helpers.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These UT/test-stub/hooks appear in the static call graph for OS_lseek (instrumentation/stubbing). They may perform string operations (registration of names/context metadata) and thus must be checked if the build under analysis includes/links these stubs.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed into the helper functions may contain buffers/fields (e.g. names or pointers) that are read/written; the structure definition is needed to see whether any string operations could access beyond bounds.

- osal_id_t: The file descriptor type; knowing its representation can be necessary to determine which code paths are taken inside ID-validation functions (and whether any string operations are used depending on ID type).

- OS_SUCCESS, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT: Constants used by OS_lseek to choose call behavior and interpret results. They are needed to understand which branches are taken (e.g., success path calls GenericSeek_Impl and Release) so the reachable functions that must be inspected for string.h usage are known.

Include the implementations or prototypes and any immediate callees of the listed functions when performing the MISRA string-rule analysis so you can determine if any memcpy/strcpy/strlen/etc. are reachable from OS_lseek and whether they can access memory out-of-bounds.
